<subSubSection id="EB58F396CC87DCC4BCF4771401BA55FE" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" type="common names">
<paragraph id="F8DA275E9C823439513C0A085B3484C2" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">Common names.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A87B3384CA47A784CEC0FAAED56A07E0" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">
United States of America. Sunberry (
<bibRefCitation id="6AC9E58701AB2393E303BAC01D7C1C01" DOI="https://doi.org/10.2307/2418547" author="Schilling, EE" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Botany" pageId="117" pageNumber="118" pagination="172 - 185" refId="B207" refString="Schilling, EE, 1981. Systematics of Solanum sect. Solanum (Solanaceae) in North America. Systematic Botany 6 (2): 172 - 185, DOI: https://doi.org/10.2307/2418547" title="Systematics of Solanum sect. Solanum (Solanaceae) in North America." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/2418547" volume="6" year="1981">Schilling 1981</bibRefCitation>
), Wonderberry (see 
<bibRefCitation id="E54E2F09507B8D72DCFBD84AFA438F02" author="Heiser, CB" journalOrPublisher="Ciencia y Naturaleza" pageId="112" pageNumber="113" refId="B107" refString="Heiser, CB, 1969. Nightshades, the paradoxical plants. WH Freeman, San Francisco." title="Nightshades, the paradoxical plants. WH Freeman, San Francisco." year="1969">Heiser 1969</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="3FF06C2DBCBB8D501CF4D2A863A9293C" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" type="uses">
<paragraph id="BE9B406C186B63368749606D762922EE" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">Uses.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="64488EDA9FEA9A7056F04B496F511AE9" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">
In its native South Africa, the berries are used for jam or as a fruit (
<bibRefCitation id="9C4F52E52FEBB0B5ECDB46DE20644368" author="Heiser, CB" journalOrPublisher="Ciencia y Naturaleza" pageId="112" pageNumber="113" refId="B107" refString="Heiser, CB, 1969. Nightshades, the paradoxical plants. WH Freeman, San Francisco." title="Nightshades, the paradoxical plants. WH Freeman, San Francisco." year="1969">Heiser 1969</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="27165E7E1FFA05F479306785840BBA1E" DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/phytokeys.106.21991" author="Saerkinen, T" journalOrPublisher="PhytoKeys" pageId="116" pageNumber="117" pagination="1 - 223" refId="B204" refString="Saerkinen, T, Poczai, P, Barboza, GE, van der Weerden, GM, Baden, M, Knapp, S, 2018. A revision of the Old World black nightshades (Morelloid clade of Solanum L., Solanaceae). PhytoKeys 106: 1 - 223, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/phytokeys.106.21991" title="A revision of the Old World black nightshades (Morelloid clade of Solanum L., Solanaceae)." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/phytokeys.106.21991" volume="106" year="2018">
<normalizedToken id="3D33B10B409714DA28DFD2E9CC684C9D" originalValue="Särkinen">Saerkinen</normalizedToken>
et al. 2018
</bibRefCitation>
); its cultivation by Luther Burbank was also as a jam fruit (
<bibRefCitation id="C70E42C30E99A9E09B4C1E1164194079" author="Heiser, CB" journalOrPublisher="Ciencia y Naturaleza" pageId="112" pageNumber="113" refId="B107" refString="Heiser, CB, 1969. Nightshades, the paradoxical plants. WH Freeman, San Francisco." title="Nightshades, the paradoxical plants. WH Freeman, San Francisco." year="1969">Heiser 1969</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6B07E8152BF0DC2D55A4DD7D3C69C917" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" type="preliminary conservation status (iucn 2017)">
<paragraph id="D2D49A9DD012547CF277CF92C7C68F75" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">
Preliminary conservation status (
<bibRefCitation id="EB48905669D2A703B64E3D80E3F3AEC6" author="IUCN" journalOrPublisher="Alaska Park Science" pageId="113" pageNumber="114" publicationUrl="http://www.iucnredlist.org/documents/RedListGuidelines.pdf" refId="B115" refString="IUCN, 2017. Guidelines for Using the IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria. Version 13. Prepared by the Standards and Petitions Subcommittee. http://www.iucnredlist.org/documents/RedListGuidelines.pdf" title="Guidelines for Using the IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria. Version 13. Prepared by the Standards and Petitions Subcommittee." url="http://www.iucnredlist.org/documents/RedListGuidelines.pdf" year="2017">IUCN 2017</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5E872D7713305AE77D58916BB9BA6D0B" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">
Least Concern (LC). 
<taxonomicName id="15A38C5E585A8743A09715F0561DAF58" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Verbenaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum retroflexum" order="Solanales" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="retroflexum">
<emphasis id="618168559CFF3979C3DB4FAF86CD895C" italics="true" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">Solanum retroflexum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a rare adventive species in North America; for conservation status in its native range see 
<bibRefCitation id="78996258E8420784F9C9C85836A792B2" DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/phytokeys.106.21991" author="Saerkinen, T" journalOrPublisher="PhytoKeys" pageId="116" pageNumber="117" pagination="1 - 223" refId="B204" refString="Saerkinen, T, Poczai, P, Barboza, GE, van der Weerden, GM, Baden, M, Knapp, S, 2018. A revision of the Old World black nightshades (Morelloid clade of Solanum L., Solanaceae). PhytoKeys 106: 1 - 223, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/phytokeys.106.21991" title="A revision of the Old World black nightshades (Morelloid clade of Solanum L., Solanaceae)." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/phytokeys.106.21991" volume="106" year="2018">
<normalizedToken id="3AA64475B042C6B20AE761C00E7987A6" originalValue="Särkinen">Saerkinen</normalizedToken>
et al. (2018)
</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="CC6A05128B4A105557D56294B4B39248" lastPageId="89" lastPageNumber="90" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="DDD89608271B18A55E869EC01BA2212F" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8259D1DDBE4EC6C59CD88335447F020D" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">
In its native range 
<taxonomicName id="42F9675C82D8BC0842029DFEBEDB2A37" family="Verbenaceae" genus="S." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. retroflexum" order="Solanales" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" rank="species" species="retroflexum">
<emphasis id="EC15D0058869803C889A3D439FF70264" italics="true" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">S. retroflexum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a species that shows great variation in its indumentum, the trichomes varying from eglandular to glandular and the leaves from nearly glabrous to densely pubescent. In the geographic region treated here, it has only been collected sporadically from cultivation and appears not to escape or naturalise. The species can be distinguished from other morelloids in North America based on a character combination of inflorescences with 1-4 flowers, filaments 1.2-1.5 mm long, strongly reflexed calyx lobes in fruit, and matte purple berries that lack stone cells and drop without the pedicels. 
<taxonomicName id="4C85CC7A6493C3D9E0E10759A5D89455" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Verbenaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum americanum" order="Solanales" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="americanum">
<emphasis id="D5B88AC9740EA45AA77FB4A70CDB437C" italics="true" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">Solanum americanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has similar small anthers and persistent pedicels, but the berries are very shiny and contain stone cells.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DDC030AC439A58378E0036CF5363DE47" lastPageId="89" lastPageNumber="90" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">
<taxonomicName id="C8DA66FBF72F989D718D4FEA26A47435" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Verbenaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum retroflexum" order="Solanales" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="retroflexum">
<emphasis id="718D44E6226DF8FF648D6005C03B2C43" italics="true" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">Solanum retroflexum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a tetraploid of uncertain parentage (see discussion in 
<bibRefCitation id="28A7BC799E7469E08C0F9AFE75CA36DD" DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/phytokeys.106.21991" author="Saerkinen, T" journalOrPublisher="PhytoKeys" pageId="116" pageNumber="117" pagination="1 - 223" refId="B204" refString="Saerkinen, T, Poczai, P, Barboza, GE, van der Weerden, GM, Baden, M, Knapp, S, 2018. A revision of the Old World black nightshades (Morelloid clade of Solanum L., Solanaceae). PhytoKeys 106: 1 - 223, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/phytokeys.106.21991" title="A revision of the Old World black nightshades (Morelloid clade of Solanum L., Solanaceae)." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/phytokeys.106.21991" volume="106" year="2018">
<normalizedToken id="A38C60C8BCD97391EBDEA2248BC89760" originalValue="Särkinen">Saerkinen</normalizedToken>
et al. 2018
</bibRefCitation>
). The berries are used in a local jam industry in South Africa (
<bibRefCitation id="652999C9D9AFD2143C9A0BF25B7DE577" author="Viljoen, E" journalOrPublisher="Genetica" pageId="119" pageNumber="120" refId="B249" refString="Viljoen, E, 2011. Morphology and genetic relationships in members of the Solanumnigrum L. complex used for jam production in the Highveld of South Africa. MSc thesis, Biotechnology, University of Pretoria, Pretoria, 1-242." title="Morphology and genetic relationships in members of the Solanumnigrum L. complex used for jam production in the Highveld of South Africa. MSc thesis, Biotechnology, University of Pretoria, Pretoria, 1 - 242." year="2011">Viljoen 2011</bibRefCitation>
) and this is the species introduced as the 
<normalizedToken id="067973195825BFA4AD22DE19B9B74392" originalValue="“wonderberry”">&quot;wonderberry&quot;</normalizedToken>
by Luther Burbank in the 1930s (
<bibRefCitation id="992E8F0F2AA43CC8A707D47C14913B5A" author="Heiser, CB" journalOrPublisher="Ciencia y Naturaleza" pageId="112" pageNumber="113" refId="B107" refString="Heiser, CB, 1969. Nightshades, the paradoxical plants. WH Freeman, San Francisco." title="Nightshades, the paradoxical plants. WH Freeman, San Francisco." year="1969">Heiser 1969</bibRefCitation>
). The story of the mystery surrounding the identity of 
<normalizedToken id="8AF7E06FB4AB80A66B59652FA0E43922" originalValue="Burbank’s">Burbank's</normalizedToken>
<pageBreakToken id="2880A640B430CA73D5D76354EDBDCC88" pageId="89" pageNumber="90" start="start">&quot;</pageBreakToken>
wonderberry&quot; is told in detail in 
<bibRefCitation id="1A063A21F0E6A0F0CC569B6D806A6AC4" author="Heiser, CB" journalOrPublisher="Ciencia y Naturaleza" pageId="112" pageNumber="113" refId="B107" refString="Heiser, CB, 1969. Nightshades, the paradoxical plants. WH Freeman, San Francisco." title="Nightshades, the paradoxical plants. WH Freeman, San Francisco." year="1969">Heiser (1969)</bibRefCitation>
; it was variously considered a fraud or a case of mistaken identity. Burbank contended he had created the 
<normalizedToken id="FE2D94B637E0DD320703974CEF2B5866" originalValue="“wonderberry”">&quot;wonderberry&quot;</normalizedToken>
through hybridisation of &quot; 
<taxonomicName id="1F97BB1E2BC59D08810077727C8DC555" family="Verbenaceae" genus="S." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. guineense" order="Solanales" pageId="89" pageNumber="90" rank="species" species="guineense">S. guineense</taxonomicName>
&quot; (= 
<taxonomicName id="455FF92EC100D218761ABD0EE599EA9D" family="Verbenaceae" genus="S." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. scabrum" order="Solanales" pageId="89" pageNumber="90" rank="species" species="scabrum">
<emphasis id="B2C981CFD539C0D79551E2E9E6BF2256" italics="true" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">S. scabrum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and &quot; 
<taxonomicName id="0DD43A671C09C21A6B1609008DBDCBBF" family="Verbenaceae" genus="S." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. villosum" order="Solanales" pageId="89" pageNumber="90" rank="species" species="villosum">S. villosum</taxonomicName>
&quot; (probably = 
<taxonomicName id="467F9A0B67B97F4CC601EBBE644EB806" family="Verbenaceae" genus="S." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. nitidibaccatum" order="Solanales" pageId="89" pageNumber="90" rank="species" species="nitidibaccatum">
<emphasis id="4ABFCB9EC0AF0EB9826EFD96CE17B636" italics="true" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">S. nitidibaccatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Various correspondents (see 
<bibRefCitation id="79F762311AF0F5A8BA94C7EA102B189E" author="Heiser, CB" journalOrPublisher="Ciencia y Naturaleza" pageId="112" pageNumber="113" refId="B107" refString="Heiser, CB, 1969. Nightshades, the paradoxical plants. WH Freeman, San Francisco." title="Nightshades, the paradoxical plants. WH Freeman, San Francisco." year="1969">Heiser 1969</bibRefCitation>
) suggested it was actually the &quot;garden huckleberry&quot; (
<taxonomicName id="E02C00C800CFBE25E916EBF4FBD1600A" family="Verbenaceae" genus="S." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. scabrum" order="Solanales" pageId="89" pageNumber="90" rank="species" species="scabrum">
<emphasis id="F5F7F5A724C067EC4552B77D9311F6B6" italics="true" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">S. scabrum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) or one of the native black nightshades from North America. 
<bibRefCitation id="0257482D98FC55CA4C47DCD5507C1FA0" author="Stebbins, GL" journalOrPublisher="Madrono" pageId="118" pageNumber="119" pagination="70 - 81" refId="B228" refString="Stebbins, GL, Paddock, EF, 1949. The Solanum nigrum complex in Pacific North America. Madrono 10: 70 - 81" title="The Solanum nigrum complex in Pacific North America." volume="10" year="1949">Stebbins and Paddock (1949)</bibRefCitation>
suggested that the true identity of the 
<normalizedToken id="8D7FEC81F5C031DFDFCCF8CAD5863160" originalValue="“wonderberry”">&quot;wonderberry&quot;</normalizedToken>
was 
<taxonomicName id="CA79F24098288CB45E5B78B30183E926" family="Verbenaceae" genus="S." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. nigrum" order="Solanales" pageId="89" pageNumber="90" rank="species" species="nigrum">
<emphasis id="2EEB7F98479357DD77C356E424E37F16" italics="true" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">S. nigrum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a species occasionally found in agricultural fields in the western United States. Examination of specimens grown from the original seeds sold by John Childs, the sole distributor of 
<normalizedToken id="FD36D84519030943CFE528B8419C3983" originalValue="Burbank’s">Burbank's</normalizedToken>
<normalizedToken id="C8776B410E2816DD7DE8FFBCBB34FE8C" originalValue="“wonderberry”">&quot;wonderberry&quot;</normalizedToken>
, have shown that these were plants of 
<taxonomicName id="B60922F5290817CA6E471FC420D930A3" family="Verbenaceae" genus="S." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. retroflexum" order="Solanales" pageId="89" pageNumber="90" rank="species" species="retroflexum">
<emphasis id="05EF46ED14807A272E8CABD2F24FF129" italics="true" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">S. retroflexum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but how Burbank came to grow them is still not known. Typification details for the synonyms of 
<taxonomicName id="1CF016514EE86B3A657B99FE064B3245" family="Verbenaceae" genus="S." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. retroflexum" order="Solanales" pageId="89" pageNumber="90" rank="species" species="retroflexum">
<emphasis id="8A442C4CF199DDC84385E12A44D06822" italics="true" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">S. retroflexum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be found in 
<bibRefCitation id="AEA829412473CCED801E58C27E8E66B9" DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/phytokeys.106.21991" author="Saerkinen, T" journalOrPublisher="PhytoKeys" pageId="116" pageNumber="117" pagination="1 - 223" refId="B204" refString="Saerkinen, T, Poczai, P, Barboza, GE, van der Weerden, GM, Baden, M, Knapp, S, 2018. A revision of the Old World black nightshades (Morelloid clade of Solanum L., Solanaceae). PhytoKeys 106: 1 - 223, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/phytokeys.106.21991" title="A revision of the Old World black nightshades (Morelloid clade of Solanum L., Solanaceae)." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/phytokeys.106.21991" volume="106" year="2018">
<normalizedToken id="4242A25C33AFB4DE98C07A8D0E4F8661" originalValue="Särkinen">Saerkinen</normalizedToken>
et al. (2018)
</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
